#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:17
msgid "Background"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:19
msgid ""
"ROS 2 breaks complex systems down into many modular nodes. Topics are a "
"vital element of the ROS graph that act as a bus for nodes to exchange "
"messages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:24
msgid ""
"A node may publish data to any number of topics and simultaneously have "
"subscriptions to any number of topics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:28
msgid ""
"Topics are one of the important ways that data moves between nodes, and "
"therefore between different parts of the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:32
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:34
msgid ""
"The :ref:`previous tutorial <ROS2Nodes>` provides some useful background "
"information on nodes that is built upon here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:36
msgid ""
"As always, don’t forget to source ROS 2 in :ref:`every new terminal you open "
"<ConfigROS2>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:39
msgid "Tasks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:42
msgid "1 Setup"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:44
msgid "By now you should be comfortable starting up turtlesim."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:46
msgid "Open a new terminal and run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:48
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtlesim_node"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:52
msgid "Open another terminal and run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:54
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtle_teleop_key"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:58
msgid ""
"Recall from the :ref:`previous tutorial <ROS2Nodes>` that the names of these "
"nodes are ``/turtlesim`` and ``/teleop_turtle`` by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:62
msgid "2 rqt_graph"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:64
msgid ""
"Throughout this tutorial, we will use ``rqt_graph`` to visualize the "
"changing nodes and topics, as well as the connections between them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:66
msgid ""
"The :ref:`turtlesim tutorial <Turtlesim>` tells you how to install rqt and "
"all its plugins, including ``rqt_graph``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:68
msgid "To run rqt_graph, open a new terminal and enter the command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:70
msgid "rqt_graph"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:74
msgid ""
"You can also open rqt_graph by opening rqt and selecting **Plugins** > "
"**Introspection** > **Nodes Graph**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:78
msgid ""
"You should see the above nodes and topic, as well as two actions around the "
"periphery of the graph (let's ignore those for now). If you hover your mouse "
"over the topic in the center, you'll see the color highlighting like in the "
"image above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:81
msgid ""
"The graph is depicting how the ``/turtlesim`` node and the ``/"
"teleop_turtle`` node are communicating with each other over a topic. The ``/"
"teleop_turtle`` node is publishing data (the keystrokes you enter to move "
"the turtle around) to the ``/turtle1/cmd_vel`` topic, and the ``/turtlesim`` "
"node is subscribed to that topic to receive the data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:84
msgid ""
"The highlighting feature of rqt_graph is very helpful when examining more "
"complex systems with many nodes and topics connected in many different ways."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:86
msgid ""
"rqt_graph is a graphical introspection tool. Now we’ll look at some command "
"line tools for introspecting topics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:91
msgid "3 ros2 topic list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:93
msgid ""
"Running the ``ros2 topic list`` command in a new terminal will return a list "
"of all the topics currently active in the system:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:95
msgid ""
"/parameter_events\n"
"/rosout\n"
"/turtle1/cmd_vel\n"
"/turtle1/color_sensor\n"
"/turtle1/pose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:103
msgid ""
"``ros2 topic list -t`` will return the same list of topics, this time with "
"the topic type appended in brackets after each:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:105
msgid ""
"/parameter_events [rcl_interfaces/msg/ParameterEvent]\n"
"/rosout [rcl_interfaces/msg/Log]\n"
"/turtle1/cmd_vel [geometry_msgs/msg/Twist]\n"
"/turtle1/color_sensor [turtlesim/msg/Color]\n"
"/turtle1/pose [turtlesim/msg/Pose]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:113
msgid ""
"Topics have names and types. These attributes, particularly the type, are "
"how nodes know they’re talking about the same information as it moves over "
"topics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:116
msgid ""
"If you’re wondering where all these topics are in rqt_graph, you can uncheck "
"all the boxes under **Hide:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:120
msgid "For now, though, leave those options checked to avoid confusion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:123
msgid "4 ros2 topic echo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:125
msgid "To see the data being published on a topic, use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:127
msgid "ros2 topic echo <topic_name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:131
msgid ""
"Since we know that ``/teleop_turtle`` publishes data to ``/turtlesim`` over "
"the ``/turtle1/cmd_vel`` topic, let's use ``echo`` to introspect on that "
"topic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:133
msgid "ros2 topic echo /turtle1/cmd_vel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:137
msgid ""
"At first, this command won’t return any data. That’s because it’s waiting "
"for ``/teleop_turtle`` to publish something."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:140
msgid ""
"Return to the terminal where ``turtle_teleop_key`` is running and use the "
"arrows to move the turtle around. Watch the terminal where your ``echo`` is "
"running at the same time, and you’ll see position data being published for "
"every movement you make:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:143
#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:212
msgid ""
"linear:\n"
"  x: 2.0\n"
"  y: 0.0\n"
"  z: 0.0\n"
"angular:\n"
"  x: 0.0\n"
"  y: 0.0\n"
"  z: 0.0\n"
"  ---"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:155
msgid "Now return to rqt_graph and uncheck the **Debug** box."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:159
msgid ""
"``/_ros2cli_26646`` is the node created by the ``echo`` we just ran (the "
"number will change). Now you can see that the publisher is publishing data "
"over the ``cmd_vel`` topic, and two subscribers are subscribed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:163
msgid "5 ros2 topic info"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:165
msgid ""
"Topics don’t have to only be point-to-point communication; it can be one-to-"
"many, many-to-one, or many-to-many."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:167
msgid "Another way to look at this is running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:169
msgid "ros2 topic info /turtle1/cmd_vel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:173
msgid "Which will return:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:175
msgid ""
"Topic: /turtle1/cmd_vel\n"
"Publisher count: 1\n"
"Subscription count: 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:182
msgid "6 ros2 interface show"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:184
msgid ""
"Nodes send data over topics using messages. Publishers and subscribers must "
"send and receive the same type of message to communicate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:187
msgid ""
"The topic types we saw earlier after running ``ros2 topic list -t`` let us "
"know what type of messages each topic can send. Recall that the ``cmd_vel`` "
"topic has the type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:190
msgid "geometry_msgs/msg/Twist"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:194
msgid ""
"This means that in the package ``geometry_msgs`` there is a ``msg`` called "
"``Twist``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:196
msgid ""
"Now we can run ``ros2 interface show <type>.msg`` on this type to learn its "
"details, specifically, what structure of data the message expects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:198
msgid "ros2 msg show geometry_msgs/msg/Twist"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:202
msgid ""
"# This expresses velocity in free space broken into its linear and angular "
"parts.\n"
"\n"
"    Vector3  linear\n"
"    Vector3  angular"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:209
msgid ""
"This tells you that the ``/turtlesim`` node is expecting a message with two "
"vectors, ``linear`` and ``angular``, of three elements each. If you recall "
"the data we saw ``/teleop_turtle`` passing to ``/turtlesim`` with the "
"``echo`` command, it’s in the same structure:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:225
msgid "7 ros2 topic pub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:227
msgid ""
"Now that you have the message structure, you can publish data onto a topic "
"directly from the command line using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:229
msgid "ros2 topic pub <topic_name> <msg_type> '<args>'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:233
msgid ""
"The ``'<args>'`` argument is the actual data you’ll pass to the topic, in "
"the structure you just discovered in the previous section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:235
msgid ""
"It’s important to note that this argument needs to be input in YAML syntax. "
"Input the full command like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:238
msgid ""
"ros2 topic pub --once /turtle1/cmd_vel geometry_msgs/msg/Twist \"{linear: "
"{x: 2.0, y: 0.0, z: 0.0}, angular: {x: 0.0, y: 0.0, z: 1.8}}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:242
msgid ""
"``--once`` is an optional argument meaning “publish one message then exit”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:244
msgid "You will receive the following message in the terminal:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:246
msgid ""
"publisher: beginning loop\n"
"publishing #1: geometry_msgs.msg.Twist(linear=geometry_msgs.msg."
"Vector3(x=2.0, y=0.0, z=0.0), angular=geometry_msgs.msg.Vector3(x=0.0, "
"y=0.0, z=1.8))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:251
msgid "And you will see your turtle move like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:255
msgid ""
"The turtle (and commonly the real robots which it is meant to emulate) "
"require a steady stream of commands to operate continuously. So, to get the "
"turtle to keep moving, you can run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:258
msgid ""
"ros2 topic pub --rate 1 /turtle1/cmd_vel geometry_msgs/msg/Twist \"{linear: "
"{x: 2.0, y: 0.0, z: 0.0}, angular: {x: 0.0, y: 0.0, z: 1.8}}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:262
msgid ""
"The difference here is the removal of the ``--once`` option and the addition "
"of the ``--rate 1`` option, which tells ``ros2 topic pub`` to publish the "
"command in a steady stream at 1 Hz."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:266
msgid ""
"You can refresh rqt_graph to see what’s happening graphically. You will see "
"the ``ros 2 topic pub ...`` node (``/_ros2cli_30358``) is publishing over "
"the ``/turtle1/cmd_vel`` topic, and is being received by both the ``ros2 "
"topic echo ...`` node (``/_ros2cli_26646``) and the ``/turtlesim`` node now."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:271
msgid ""
"Finally, you can run ``echo`` on the ``pose`` topic and recheck rqt_graph:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:273
msgid "ros2 topic echo /turtle1/pose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:279
msgid ""
"In this case, ``/turtlesim`` is now publishing to the ``pose`` topic, and a "
"new ``echo`` node is subscribed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:282
msgid "8 ros2 topic hz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:284
msgid ""
"For one last introspection on this process, you can report the rate at which "
"data is published using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:286
msgid "ros2 topic hz /turtle1/pose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:290
msgid ""
"It will return data on the rate at which the ``/turtlesim`` node is "
"publishing data to the ``pose`` topic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:292
msgid ""
"average rate: 59.354\n"
"  min: 0.005s max: 0.027s std dev: 0.00284s window: 58"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Topics/Understanding-ROS2-Topics.rst:297
msgid ""
"Recall that you set the rate of ``turtle1/cmd_vel`` to publish at a steady 1 "
"Hz using ``ros2 topic pub --rate 1``. If you run the above command with "
"``turtle1/cmd_vel`` instead of ``turtle1/pose``, you will see an average "
"reflecting that rate."
msgstr ""

